      'content': '# Introduction to Physical Properties\n\n## What are Physical Properties?\n\n**Physical properties** are characteristics of a material that can be observed or measured WITHOUT changing the material's identity.\n\n### Key Point:\n- Physical properties help us **identify**, **classify**, and **choose** materials for specific uses\n- They can be measured using scientific instruments\n- The material remains the same substance after measurement\n\n---\n\n## Common Physical Properties\n\nWe will study these important physical properties:\n\n1. **Electrical Conductivity** - Can it conduct electricity?\n2. **Thermal Conductivity** - Can it conduct heat?\n3. **Density** - How heavy is it for its size?\n4. **Melting Point** - At what temperature does it melt?\n5. **Boiling Point** - At what temperature does it boil?\n6. **Strength** - How much force can it withstand? (G3)\n7. **Hardness** - How resistant is it to scratching? (G3)\n8. **Flexibility** - Can it bend without breaking? (G3)\n\n---\n\n## Why are Physical Properties Important?\n\n### In Daily Life:\n- **Cooking pots** are made of metal (good thermal conductor)\n- **Electrical wires** use copper (good electrical conductor)\n- **Drink bottles** use plastic (lightweight, flexible)\n- **Building foundations** use concrete (strong, hard)\n\n### In Singapore:\n- **HDB buildings** use steel and concrete (strong, durable)\n- **MRT tracks** use steel (hard, strong)\n- **Water pipes** use PVC plastic (doesn't rust, flexible)\n- **Electrical cables** use copper wires with plastic insulation\n\n---\n\n## Physical vs Chemical Properties\n\n| Physical Properties | Chemical Properties |\n|-------------------|-------------------|\n| Can be observed WITHOUT changing the substance | Can ONLY be observed when substance changes |\n| Examples: color, density, melting point | Examples: flammability, reactivity |\n| Material stays the same | Material becomes different substance |\n| Measuring density of iron | Rusting of iron |',
      'content_zh': '# 物理性质简介\n\n## 什么是物理性质？\n\n**物理性质**是材料的特征，可以在不改变材料身份的情况下观察或测量。\n\n### 要点：\n- 物理性质帮助我们**识别**、**分类**和**选择**用于特定用途的材料\n- 可以使用科学仪器测量\n- 测量后材料保持相同的物质\n\n---\n\n## 常见的物理性质\n\n我们将学习这些重要的物理性质：\n\n1. **电导率** - 能导电吗？\n2. **热导率** - 能导热吗？\n3. **密度** - 相对于其大小有多重？\n4. **熔点** - 在什么温度下熔化？\n5. **沸点** - 在什么温度下沸腾？\n6. **强度** - 能承受多大的力？（G3）\n7. **硬度** - 对划痕的抵抗力有多强？（G3）\n8. **柔韧性** - 能不断裂地弯曲吗？（G3）\n\n---\n\n## 为什么物理性质很重要？\n\n### 在日常生活中：\n- **锅**由金属制成（良好的热导体）\n- **电线**使用铜（良好的电导体）\n- **饮料瓶**使用塑料（轻便、柔韧）\n- **建筑地基**使用混凝土（坚固、坚硬）\n\n### 在新加坡：\n- **组屋建筑**使用钢和混凝土（坚固、耐用）\n- **地铁轨道**使用钢（坚硬、坚固）\n- **水管**使用PVC塑料（不生锈、柔韧）\n- **电缆**使用带塑料绝缘的铜线\n\n---\n\n## 物理性质与化学性质\n\n| 物理性质 | 化学性质 |\n|-------------------|-------------------|\n| 可以在不改变物质的情况下观察 | 只能在物质改变时观察 |\n| 例子：颜色、密度、熔点 | 例子：可燃性、反应性 |\n| 材料保持不变 | 材料变成不同的物质 |\n| 测量铁的密度 | 铁生锈 |'
