    {
      'type': 'text',
      'content': '# Electrical Conductivity\n\n## What is Electrical Conductivity?\n\n**Electrical conductivity** is the ability of a material to allow electric current to flow through it.\n\n- **Good conductors**: Allow electricity to flow easily\n- **Poor conductors (insulators)**: Do not allow electricity to flow easily\n\n---\n\n## Electrical Conductors\n\n### Metals are Good Conductors\n\n**Why?** Metals have **free electrons** that can move easily through the material.\n\n**Examples:**\n- **Copper** - Best common conductor, used in electrical wires\n- **Aluminum** - Lightweight conductor, used in power cables\n- **Silver** - Best conductor but too expensive\n- **Gold** - Excellent conductor, doesn't corrode, used in electronic chips\n- **Iron/Steel** - Moderate conductor\n\n### Singapore Context:\n**Power cables** along HDB blocks and streets use aluminum or copper cores because they conduct electricity efficiently over long distances.\n\n---\n\n## Electrical Insulators\n\n### Non-Metals are Poor Conductors\n\n**Why?** Non-metals have electrons that are tightly bound to atoms and cannot move freely.\n\n**Examples:**\n- **Plastic** - Used to coat electrical wires (insulation)\n- **Rubber** - Used in electrician's gloves\n- **Glass** - Used in electrical insulators on power poles\n- **Wood (dry)** - Poor conductor\n- **Air** - Very poor conductor\n\n### Safety Application:\n**Electrical wires** have a copper core (conductor) covered with plastic (insulator). This allows electricity to flow through the copper while keeping you safe from electric shock!\n\n---\n\n## Special Cases\n\n### Graphite (Carbon)\n**Unusual!** Graphite is a non-metal but conducts electricity!\n- Used in pencil leads\n- Used in batteries\n- Used in electric motors (brushes)\n\n### Water\n- **Pure water**: Poor conductor\n- **Tap water**: Good conductor (contains dissolved ions)\n- **Seawater**: Excellent conductor (high salt content)\n\n**Singapore Safety:** Never use electrical devices near water (bathrooms, pools, kitchen sinks)!\n\n---\n\n## Testing Electrical Conductivity\n\n### Simple Circuit Test:\n\n1. Set up a simple circuit: Battery → Bulb → Test Material → back to Battery\n2. Place the material between two wires\n3. Observe:\n   - **Bulb lights up brightly** → Good conductor\n   - **Bulb lights up dimly** → Moderate conductor\n   - **Bulb doesn't light up** → Insulator\n\n### Safety:\n- Only use low-voltage batteries (1.5V)\n- NEVER test with mains electricity (230V) - DANGEROUS!',
      'content_zh': '# 电导率\n\n## 什么是电导率？\n\n**电导率**是材料允许电流通过的能力。\n\n- **良导体**：让电流容易流过\n- **不良导体（绝缘体）**：不让电流容易流过\n\n---\n\n## 电导体\n\n### 金属是良好的导体\n\n**为什么？** 金属有可以在材料中轻易移动的**自由电子**。\n\n**例子：**\n- **铜** - 最好的常见导体，用于电线\n- **铝** - 轻质导体，用于电力电缆\n- **银** - 最好的导体但太贵\n- **金** - 优秀的导体，不腐蚀，用于电子芯片\n- **铁/钢** - 中等导体\n\n### 新加坡背景：\n沿着组屋和街道的**电力电缆**使用铝或铜芯，因为它们能高效地远距离传输电力。\n\n---\n\n## 电绝缘体\n\n### 非金属是不良导体\n\n**为什么？** 非金属的电子与原子紧密结合，不能自由移动。\n\n**例子：**\n- **塑料** - 用于包裹电线（绝缘）\n- **橡胶** - 用于电工手套\n- **玻璃** - 用于电线杆上的电气绝缘子\n- **木头（干燥）** - 不良导体\n- **空气** - 非常不良导体\n\n### 安全应用：\n**电线**有铜芯（导体）外覆塑料（绝缘体）。这允许电流通过铜流动，同时保护你免受触电！\n\n---\n\n## 特殊情况\n\n### 石墨（碳）\n**不寻常！** 石墨是非金属但能导电！\n- 用于铅笔芯\n- 用于电池\n- 用于电动机（电刷）\n\n### 水\n- **纯水**：不良导体\n- **自来水**：良好导体（含有溶解的离子）\n- **海水**：优秀导体（高盐含量）\n\n**新加坡安全：** 切勿在水附近使用电气设备（浴室、泳池、厨房水槽）！\n\n---\n\n## 测试电导率\n\n### 简单的电路测试：\n\n1. 设置简单电路：电池 → 灯泡 → 测试材料 → 返回电池\n2. 将材料放在两根导线之间\n3. 观察：\n   - **灯泡明亮发光** → 良导体\n   - **灯泡微弱发光** → 中等导体\n   - **灯泡不发光** → 绝缘体\n\n### 安全：\n- 只使用低压电池（1.5V）\n- 切勿使用市电（230V）进行测试 - 危险！'
