    {
      'type': 'text',
      'content': '# Thermal Conductivity\n\n## What is Thermal Conductivity?\n\n**Thermal conductivity** is the ability of a material to conduct (transfer) heat energy.\n\n- **Good thermal conductors**: Heat passes through quickly\n- **Poor thermal conductors (thermal insulators)**: Heat passes through slowly\n\n---\n\n## Thermal Conductors\n\n### Metals are Good Thermal Conductors\n\n**Why?** Free electrons in metals transfer kinetic energy quickly.\n\n**Ranking (Best to Good):**\n1. **Silver** - Best thermal conductor (but expensive)\n2. **Copper** - Excellent and affordable\n3. **Aluminum** - Good and lightweight\n4. **Iron/Steel** - Moderate\n\n### Applications:\n\n**Cooking Utensils (Singapore Context):**\n- **Wok/Frying pans**: Aluminum or stainless steel (heats up quickly)\n- **Pot handles**: Often wrapped in wood or plastic (stays cool)\n- **Steamer baskets**: Metal conducts steam heat evenly\n\n**Heat Sinks:**\n- Computer CPUs use aluminum/copper heat sinks\n- Air-con condensers use aluminum fins\n\n**Industrial:**\n- Heat exchangers in factories\n- Radiators in vehicles\n\n---\n\n## Thermal Insulators\n\n### Non-Metals are Poor Thermal Conductors\n\n**Good Insulators:**\n- **Wood** - Traditional pot handles\n- **Plastic** - Modern pot handles, cooler bags\n- **Rubber** - Oven mitts\n- **Fabric/Cloth** - Tea towels, pot holders\n- **Styrofoam** - Food containers (keeps food warm/cold)\n- **Air** - Excellent insulator!\n\n### Singapore Applications:\n\n**Keeping Cool:**\n- **Cooler bags** for groceries (insulated lining)\n- **Thermal flasks** for cold/hot drinks (vacuum/air gap)\n- **Building insulation** reduces air-con costs\n\n**Keeping Warm:**\n- **Food delivery bags** (insulated to keep food hot)\n- **Thermal containers** for bringing lunch to school/work\n\n---\n\n## Testing Thermal Conductivity\n\n### Method 1: The Butter Test\n\n1. Take rods of different materials (metal, wood, plastic)\n2. Place one end of each rod in hot water\n3. Put a small piece of butter on the other end\n4. Observe which butter melts first:\n   - **Metal rod** → Butter melts quickly (good conductor)\n   - **Plastic rod** → Butter melts slowly (insulator)\n   - **Wood rod** → Butter melts very slowly (insulator)\n\n### Method 2: The Heat Spread Test\n\n1. Heat one spot on different materials\n2. Use temperature sensors at different distances\n3. Measure how quickly heat spreads\n\n---\n\n## Why Materials Differ\n\n### Good Conductors (Metals):\n- Free electrons move and transfer energy quickly\n- Atoms are closely packed\n- Regular structure allows easy energy transfer\n\n### Poor Conductors (Non-metals):\n- No free electrons\n- Atoms/molecules may be far apart (like in air, foam)\n- Irregular structure slows energy transfer\n\n---\n\n## Comparing Electrical and Thermal Conductivity\n\n| Material | Electrical | Thermal | Why? |\n|----------|-----------|---------|------|\n| **Copper** | Excellent | Excellent | Free electrons transfer both |\n| **Aluminum** | Excellent | Excellent | Free electrons transfer both |\n| **Wood** | Poor | Poor | No free electrons, irregular structure |\n| **Water** | Moderate | Poor | Has ions but molecules don't transfer heat well |\n| **Diamond** | Poor | Excellent | No free electrons BUT rigid structure transfers vibrations |\n\n**General Rule:** Good electrical conductors are usually good thermal conductors (exception: diamond).',
      'content_zh': '# 热导率\n\n## 什么是热导率？\n\n**热导率**是材料传导（传递）热能的能力。\n\n- **良好的热导体**：热量快速通过\n- **不良的热导体（热绝缘体）**：热量缓慢通过\n\n---\n\n## 热导体\n\n### 金属是良好的热导体\n\n**为什么？** 金属中的自由电子快速传递动能。\n\n**排名（最好到好）：**\n1. **银** - 最好的热导体（但昂贵）\n2. **铜** - 优秀且实惠\n3. **铝** - 良好且轻便\n4. **铁/钢** - 中等\n\n### 应用：\n\n**烹饪器具（新加坡背景）：**\n- **炒锅/煎锅**：铝或不锈钢（加热快）\n- **锅柄**：通常用木头或塑料包裹（保持凉爽）\n- **蒸笼**：金属均匀传导蒸汽热\n\n**散热器：**\n- 计算机CPU使用铝/铜散热器\n- 空调冷凝器使用铝翅片\n\n**工业：**\n- 工厂中的热交换器\n- 车辆中的散热器\n\n---\n\n## 热绝缘体\n\n### 非金属是不良的热导体\n\n**良好的绝缘体：**\n- **木头** - 传统锅柄\n- **塑料** - 现代锅柄、保冷袋\n- **橡胶** - 烤箱手套\n- **织物/布** - 茶巾、锅垫\n- **泡沫塑料** - 食品容器（保持食物温热/冷）\n- **空气** - 优秀的绝缘体！\n\n### 新加坡应用：\n\n**保持凉爽：**\n- **保冷袋**用于杂货（绝缘衬里）\n- **保温瓶**用于冷/热饮料（真空/空气间隙）\n- **建筑绝缘**降低空调成本\n\n**保持温暖：**\n- **食品配送袋**（绝缘以保持食物热）\n- **保温容器**用于带午餐到学校/工作\n\n---\n\n## 测试热导率\n\n### 方法1：黄油测试\n\n1. 取不同材料的棒（金属、木头、塑料）\n2. 将每根棒的一端放入热水中\n3. 在另一端放一小块黄油\n4. 观察哪个黄油先融化：\n   - **金属棒** → 黄油快速融化（良导体）\n   - **塑料棒** → 黄油缓慢融化（绝缘体）\n   - **木棒** → 黄油非常缓慢融化（绝缘体）\n\n### 方法2：热扩散测试\n\n1. 在不同材料的一个点加热\n2. 在不同距离使用温度传感器\n3. 测量热量扩散的速度\n\n---\n\n## 为什么材料不同\n\n### 良导体（金属）：\n- 自由电子移动并快速传递能量\n- 原子紧密堆积\n- 规则结构允许容易的能量传递\n\n### 不良导体（非金属）：\n- 没有自由电子\n- 原子/分子可能相距很远（如空气、泡沫）\n- 不规则结构减慢能量传递\n\n---\n\n## 比较电导率和热导率\n\n| 材料 | 电导率 | 热导率 | 为什么？ |\n|----------|-----------|---------|------|\n| **铜** | 优秀 | 优秀 | 自由电子传递两者 |\n| **铝** | 优秀 | 优秀 | 自由电子传递两者 |\n| **木头** | 不良 | 不良 | 没有自由电子，不规则结构 |\n| **水** | 中等 | 不良 | 有离子但分子不能很好地传递热量 |\n| **钻石** | 不良 | 优秀 | 没有自由电子但刚性结构传递振动 |\n\n**一般规则：** 良好的电导体通常是良好的热导体（例外：钻石）。'
