    {
      'type': 'text',
      'content': '# Density\n\n## What is Density?\n\n**Density** is the amount of mass in a given volume of a substance.\n\n**Formula:**\n```\nDensity = Mass / Volume\nρ = m / V\n```\n\n**SI Units:**\n- Mass: kilogram (kg) or gram (g)\n- Volume: cubic meter (m³) or cubic centimeter (cm³)\n- Density: kg/m³ or g/cm³\n\n**Conversion:** 1 g/cm³ = 1000 kg/m³\n\n---\n\n## Understanding Density\n\n### Key Concepts:\n\n**High Density:**\n- More mass packed into the same volume\n- Feels heavier for its size\n- Examples: gold, lead, iron\n\n**Low Density:**\n- Less mass in the same volume\n- Feels lighter for its size\n- Examples: cork, wood, foam, air\n\n### Analogy:\nImagine two identical boxes:\n- Box A filled with feathers (low density)\n- Box B filled with stones (high density)\n\nSame volume, but Box B has much more mass → higher density!\n\n---\n\n## Common Densities (at room temperature)\n\n### Solids:\n- **Gold**: 19.3 g/cm³\n- **Lead**: 11.3 g/cm³\n- **Iron/Steel**: 7.8 g/cm³\n- **Aluminum**: 2.7 g/cm³\n- **Ice**: 0.92 g/cm³ (less dense than water!)\n- **Wood**: 0.4-0.8 g/cm³ (varies by type)\n- **Cork**: 0.24 g/cm³\n\n### Liquids:\n- **Mercury**: 13.6 g/cm³\n- **Water**: 1.0 g/cm³ (reference value)\n- **Cooking oil**: 0.92 g/cm³\n- **Alcohol**: 0.79 g/cm³\n\n### Gases (at room temperature, 1 atm):\n- **Air**: 0.0012 g/cm³\n- **Carbon dioxide**: 0.0018 g/cm³\n- **Helium**: 0.00016 g/cm³\n\n---\n\n## Measuring Density\n\n### For Regular-Shaped Objects:\n\n**Example: Rectangular block**\n\n1. **Measure mass** using electronic balance\n2. **Calculate volume**: V = length × width × height\n3. **Calculate density**: ρ = m / V\n\n**Singapore Example:**\nA rectangular eraser measures 5 cm × 2 cm × 1 cm and has mass 10 g.\n- Volume = 5 × 2 × 1 = 10 cm³\n- Density = 10 g / 10 cm³ = 1.0 g/cm³\n\n### For Irregular-Shaped Objects:\n\n**Method: Water Displacement**\n\n1. **Measure mass** using balance\n2. **Measure volume** using displacement:\n   - Fill measuring cylinder with water, record initial volume\n   - Submerge object completely\n   - Record final volume\n   - Volume of object = Final volume - Initial volume\n3. **Calculate density**: ρ = m / V\n\n**Example:**\nA stone has mass 40 g.\n- Initial water level: 50 cm³\n- Final water level: 70 cm³\n- Volume = 70 - 50 = 20 cm³\n- Density = 40 g / 20 cm³ = 2.0 g/cm³\n\n### For Liquids:\n\n1. **Measure mass of empty measuring cylinder**\n2. **Pour liquid into cylinder, record volume**\n3. **Measure total mass** (cylinder + liquid)\n4. **Calculate mass of liquid**: m_liquid = total mass - cylinder mass\n5. **Calculate density**: ρ = m / V\n\n---\n\n## Density and Floating/Sinking\n\n### Principle:\n- Object **less dense** than liquid → **floats**\n- Object **more dense** than liquid → **sinks**\n- Object **same density** as liquid → **suspended**\n\n### Examples in Water (density = 1.0 g/cm³):\n\n**Floats:**\n- Ice (0.92 g/cm³) - This is why icebergs float!\n- Wood (0.4-0.8 g/cm³) - Ships made of wood\n- Oil (0.92 g/cm³) - Oil floats on water in spills\n- Cork (0.24 g/cm³) - Used in life jackets\n\n**Sinks:**\n- Iron (7.8 g/cm³) - Iron nail sinks\n- Aluminum (2.7 g/cm³) - Aluminum foil ball sinks\n- Stones (2-3 g/cm³) - Stones sink in water\n\n### Singapore Context:\n**Why do ships float?**\n\nIron ships in Singapore's harbor float because:\n- Solid iron sinks (density 7.8 g/cm³)\n- But ships are hollow (contain lots of air)\n- Average density of ship (iron + air) < 1.0 g/cm³\n- Therefore ship floats!\n\n**HDB Example:**\nA concrete block (density ~2.4 g/cm³) sinks in water, but the HDB building foundation stays in place because it's designed to distribute weight, not float!\n\n---\n\n## Applications of Density\n\n### 1. Material Identification\nSuspect this metal is gold? Measure its density!\n- If ρ = 19.3 g/cm³ → Likely real gold\n- If ρ = 8-10 g/cm³ → Fake (probably brass)\n\n### 2. Quality Control\nFood manufacturers check density to:\n- Detect adulteration (mixing cheap ingredients)\n- Ensure consistent product quality\n\n### 3. Engineering\n- **Airplanes**: Use low-density aluminum (lightweight but strong)\n- **Bulletproof vests**: Use high-density materials to stop bullets\n- **Life jackets**: Use very low-density foam\n\n### 4. Everyday Singapore:\n- **Hawker center oil**: Cooking oil floats on top of dishwater (less dense)\n- **Kopi/Teh**: Sugar syrup sinks to bottom (more dense than coffee/tea) - need to stir!\n- **Swimming pools**: You float more easily in seawater (Marina Bay) than freshwater pool (higher density due to salt)',
      'content_zh': '# 密度\n\n## 什么是密度？\n\n**密度**是物质在给定体积中的质量。\n\n**公式：**\n```\n密度 = 质量 / 体积\nρ = m / V\n```\n\n**国际单位：**\n- 质量：千克 (kg) 或克 (g)\n- 体积：立方米 (m³) 或立方厘米 (cm³)\n- 密度：kg/m³ 或 g/cm³\n\n**转换：** 1 g/cm³ = 1000 kg/m³\n\n---\n\n## 理解密度\n\n### 关键概念：\n\n**高密度：**\n- 相同体积中堆积更多质量\n- 感觉更重\n- 例子：金、铅、铁\n\n**低密度：**\n- 相同体积中质量较少\n- 感觉更轻\n- 例子：软木、木头、泡沫、空气\n\n### 类比：\n想象两个相同的盒子：\n- 盒子A装满羽毛（低密度）\n- 盒子B装满石头（高密度）\n\n相同的体积，但盒子B有更多的质量 → 更高的密度！\n\n---\n\n## 常见密度（室温下）\n\n### 固体：\n- **金**：19.3 g/cm³\n- **铅**：11.3 g/cm³\n- **铁/钢**：7.8 g/cm³\n- **铝**：2.7 g/cm³\n- **冰**：0.92 g/cm³（比水密度小！）\n- **木头**：0.4-0.8 g/cm³（因类型而异）\n- **软木**：0.24 g/cm³\n\n### 液体：\n- **汞**：13.6 g/cm³\n- **水**：1.0 g/cm³（参考值）\n- **食用油**：0.92 g/cm³\n- **酒精**：0.79 g/cm³\n\n### 气体（室温，1 atm）：\n- **空气**：0.0012 g/cm³\n- **二氧化碳**：0.0018 g/cm³\n- **氦气**：0.00016 g/cm³\n\n---\n\n## 测量密度\n\n### 对于规则形状物体：\n\n**例子：矩形块**\n\n1. **使用电子天平测量质量**\n2. **计算体积**：V = 长度 × 宽度 × 高度\n3. **计算密度**：ρ = m / V\n\n**新加坡例子：**\n一块矩形橡皮擦尺寸为5厘米 × 2厘米 × 1厘米，质量为10克。\n- 体积 = 5 × 2 × 1 = 10 cm³\n- 密度 = 10 g / 10 cm³ = 1.0 g/cm³\n\n### 对于不规则形状物体：\n\n**方法：水位移法**\n\n1. **使用天平测量质量**\n2. **使用位移法测量体积**：\n   - 在量筒中注入水，记录初始体积\n   - 完全浸没物体\n   - 记录最终体积\n   - 物体体积 = 最终体积 - 初始体积\n3. **计算密度**：ρ = m / V\n\n**例子：**\n一块石头质量为40克。\n- 初始水位：50 cm³\n- 最终水位：70 cm³\n- 体积 = 70 - 50 = 20 cm³\n- 密度 = 40 g / 20 cm³ = 2.0 g/cm³\n\n### 对于液体：\n\n1. **测量空量筒的质量**\n2. **将液体倒入量筒，记录体积**\n3. **测量总质量**（量筒 + 液体）\n4. **计算液体质量**：m_液体 = 总质量 - 量筒质量\n5. **计算密度**：ρ = m / V\n\n---\n\n## 密度与浮沉\n\n### 原理：\n- 物体**密度小于**液体 → **漂浮**\n- 物体**密度大于**液体 → **下沉**\n- 物体**密度等于**液体 → **悬浮**\n\n### 水中的例子（密度 = 1.0 g/cm³）：\n\n**漂浮：**\n- 冰（0.92 g/cm³）- 这就是冰山漂浮的原因！\n- 木头（0.4-0.8 g/cm³）- 木制船\n- 油（0.92 g/cm³）- 油泄漏时漂浮在水上\n- 软木（0.24 g/cm³）- 用于救生衣\n\n**下沉：**\n- 铁（7.8 g/cm³）- 铁钉下沉\n- 铝（2.7 g/cm³）- 铝箔球下沉\n- 石头（2-3 g/cm³）- 石头在水中下沉\n\n### 新加坡背景：\n**为什么船会漂浮？**\n\n新加坡港口的铁船漂浮因为：\n- 固体铁会下沉（密度7.8 g/cm³）\n- 但船是空心的（含有大量空气）\n- 船的平均密度（铁 + 空气）< 1.0 g/cm³\n- 因此船漂浮！\n\n**组屋例子：**\n混凝土块（密度~2.4 g/cm³）在水中下沉，但组屋建筑地基保持在原位，因为它被设计成分散重量，而不是漂浮！\n\n---\n\n## 密度的应用\n\n### 1. 材料识别\n怀疑这块金属是黄金？测量它的密度！\n- 如果 ρ = 19.3 g/cm³ → 可能是真金\n- 如果 ρ = 8-10 g/cm³ → 假的（可能是黄铜）\n\n### 2. 质量控制\n食品制造商检查密度以：\n- 检测掺假（混合廉价成分）\n- 确保一致的产品质量\n\n### 3. 工程\n- **飞机**：使用低密度铝（轻便但坚固）\n- **防弹背心**：使用高密度材料阻止子弹\n- **救生衣**：使用非常低密度的泡沫\n\n### 4. 日常新加坡：\n- **小贩中心油**：食用油漂浮在洗碗水上方（密度较小）\n- **咖啡/茶**：糖浆沉到底部（比咖啡/茶密度大）- 需要搅拌！\n- **游泳池**：在海水（滨海湾）中比淡水泳池更容易漂浮（因盐而密度更高）'
