      'type': 'text',
      'content': '# Melting Point and Boiling Point\n\n## Melting Point\n\n**Definition:** The temperature at which a solid changes to a liquid.\n\n### Key Points:\n- At melting point: solid and liquid coexist\n- Pure substances have **sharp** melting points\n- Mixtures have **range** of melting points\n- Melting point = freezing point (same temperature, opposite process)\n\n### Common Melting Points:\n\n| Substance | Melting Point (°C) |\n|-----------|-------------------|\n| **Ice (water)** | 0 |\n| **Butter** | 32-35 |\n| **Chocolate** | 30-32 |\n| **Aluminum** | 660 |\n| **Gold** | 1064 |\n| **Iron** | 1538 |\n| **Diamond (carbon)** | 3550 |\n\n### Singapore Context:\n**Why does chocolate melt in your pocket?**\n- Body temperature: ~37°C\n- Chocolate melting point: ~32°C\n- Since 37 > 32, chocolate melts!\n\n**Butter in hawker centers:**\nDuring hot afternoons (35°C), butter softens because it's near its melting point!\n\n---\n\n## Boiling Point\n\n**Definition:** The temperature at which a liquid changes to a gas throughout the liquid (not just surface).\n\n### Key Points:\n- At boiling point: liquid and gas coexist\n- Pure substances have **sharp** boiling points\n- Mixtures have **range** of boiling points\n- Boiling point depends on atmospheric pressure\n\n### Common Boiling Points (at 1 atm):\n\n| Substance | Boiling Point (°C) |\n|-----------|-------------------|\n| **Alcohol (ethanol)** | 78 |\n| **Water** | 100 |\n| **Cooking oil** | ~300 |\n| **Mercury** | 357 |\n| **Iron** | 2862 |\n\n### Singapore Context:\n**Cooking at different elevations:**\n- At sea level (Singapore): Water boils at 100°C\n- At high altitude: Water boils at lower temperature (less atmospheric pressure)\n- Pressure cookers raise boiling point → food cooks faster!\n\n**Steaming food:**\nSteam temperature = 100°C (at Singapore's sea level), perfect for steaming dim sum and bao!\n\n---\n\n## Using Melting/Boiling Points to Identify Substances\n\n### Example:\nYou have a clear liquid. Is it water or alcohol?\n\n**Test:**\n1. Heat the liquid carefully\n2. Measure the temperature when it boils\n3. If boils at 78°C → Alcohol\n4. If boils at 100°C → Water\n\n### Purity Testing:\n**Pure water** boils at exactly 100°C (at 1 atm).\n- If \'water\' boils at 102°C → Contains impurities (like salt)\n- If \'water\' boils over range 98-105°C → Mixture of substances\n\n### Material Selection:\n**Choosing materials for specific uses:**\n\n**Cooking pot material:**\n- Must have melting point >> 300°C (higher than cooking oil)\n- Aluminum (660°C) ✓\n- Plastic (120-180°C) ✗ Would melt!\n\n**Electrical fuse wire:**\n- Should have low melting point (to melt and break circuit when overheated)\n- Lead-tin alloy (~180°C) is commonly used\n\n---\n\n## Phase Changes Diagram\n\n```\nSOLID --[heating, melting point]--> LIQUID --[heating, boiling point]--> GAS\n       <--[cooling, freezing point]--        <--[cooling, condensing point]--\n```\n\n**Energy during phase changes:**\n- Temperature stays **constant** during melting/boiling\n- Energy is used to break bonds between particles\n- Once phase change completes, temperature rises again',
      'content_zh': '# 熔点和沸点\n\n## 熔点\n\n**定义：** 固体变成液体的温度。\n\n### 要点：\n- 在熔点：固体和液体共存\n- 纯物质有**明确的**熔点\n- 混合物有熔点**范围**\n- 熔点 = 凝固点（相同温度，相反过程）\n\n### 常见熔点：\n\n| 物质 | 熔点 (°C) |\n|-----------|-------------------|\n| **冰（水）** | 0 |\n| **黄油** | 32-35 |\n| **巧克力** | 30-32 |\n| **铝** | 660 |\n| **金** | 1064 |\n| **铁** | 1538 |\n| **钻石（碳）** | 3550 |\n\n### 新加坡背景：\n**为什么巧克力在你的口袋里融化？**\n- 体温：~37°C\n- 巧克力熔点：~32°C\n- 因为 37 > 32，巧克力融化！\n\n**小贩中心的黄油：**\n在炎热的下午（35°C），黄油会软化，因为它接近熔点！\n\n---\n\n## 沸点\n\n**定义：** 液体在整个液体中（不仅仅是表面）变成气体的温度。\n\n### 要点：\n- 在沸点：液体和气体共存\n- 纯物质有**明确的**沸点\n- 混合物有沸点**范围**\n- 沸点取决于大气压力\n\n### 常见沸点（在1 atm）：\n\n| 物质 | 沸点 (°C) |\n|-----------|-------------------|\n| **酒精（乙醇）** | 78 |\n| **水** | 100 |\n| **食用油** | ~300 |\n| **汞** | 357 |\n| **铁** | 2862 |\n\n### 新加坡背景：\n**在不同海拔烹饪：**\n- 在海平面（新加坡）：水在100°C沸腾\n- 在高海拔：水在较低温度沸腾（大气压力较小）\n- 高压锅提高沸点 → 食物煮得更快！\n\n**蒸食物：**\n蒸汽温度 = 100°C（在新加坡的海平面），非常适合蒸点心和包子！\n\n---\n\n## 使用熔点/沸点识别物质\n\n### 例子：\n你有一种透明液体。是水还是酒精？\n\n**测试：**\n1. 小心加热液体\n2. 测量液体沸腾时的温度\n3. 如果在78°C沸腾 → 酒精\n4. 如果在100°C沸腾 → 水\n\n### 纯度测试：\n**纯水**在恰好100°C沸腾（在1 atm）。\n- 如果'水'在102°C沸腾 → 含有杂质（如盐）\n- 如果'水'在98-105°C范围沸腾 → 物质混合物\n\n### 材料选择：\n**为特定用途选择材料：**\n\n**烹饪锅材料：**\n- 必须有熔点 >> 300°C（高于食用油）\n- 铝（660°C）✓\n- 塑料（120-180°C）✗ 会融化！\n\n**电保险丝线：**\n- 应该有低熔点（过热时融化并断开电路）\n- 铅锡合金（~180°C）通常使用\n\n---\n\n## 相变图\n\n```\n固体 --[加热，熔点]--> 液体 --[加热，沸点]--> 气体\n       <--[冷却，凝固点]--        <--[冷却，冷凝点]--\n```\n\n**相变期间的能量：**\n- 温度在熔化/沸腾期间保持**恒定**\n- 能量用于打破粒子之间的键\n- 一旦相变完成，温度再次上升'
