    {
      'type': 'text',
      'content': '# Strength, Hardness, and Flexibility (G3)\n\nNote: This section is **optional for G2** students but required for G3.\n\n---\n\n## Strength\n\n**Definition:** The ability of a material to withstand an applied force without breaking.\n\n### Types of Strength:\n\n**1. Tensile Strength** (pulling)\n- How much pulling force before it breaks\n- Important for: ropes, cables, chains\n\n**2. Compressive Strength** (pushing/squeezing)\n- How much squeezing force before it collapses\n- Important for: building pillars, foundations\n\n**3. Shear Strength** (cutting)\n- How much force before it breaks by sliding\n- Important for: bolts, rivets\n\n### Examples:\n\n**High Strength:**\n- Steel - Used in HDB building framework\n- Concrete - Used in foundations\n- Kevlar - Used in bulletproof vests\n- Spider silk - Stronger than steel (by weight!)\n\n**Low Strength:**\n- Paper - Tears easily\n- Foam - Collapses under weight\n- Clay - Breaks with little force\n\n### Singapore Applications:\n\n**MRT Tracks:**\n- Must have high compressive strength (heavy trains)\n- Steel alloys are used\n\n**Suspension Bridges:**\n- Cables need high tensile strength\n- Made of twisted steel wires\n\n**HDB Walls:**\n- Concrete has high compressive strength\n- Steel reinforcement bars add tensile strength\n\n---\n\n## Hardness\n\n**Definition:** The ability of a material to resist scratching, indentation, or being worn away.\n\n### Mohs Scale of Hardness (1-10):\n\n| Level | Material | Can Scratch? |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| 1 | **Talc** | Fingernail scratches it |\n| 2 | **Gypsum** | Fingernail scratches it |\n| 3 | **Calcite** | Copper coin scratches it |\n| 4 | **Fluorite** | Knife scratches it |\n| 5 | **Apatite** | Knife scratches it with difficulty |\n| 6 | **Feldspar** | Scratches glass |\n| 7 | **Quartz** | Scratches glass easily |\n| 8 | **Topaz** | Scratches quartz |\n| 9 | **Corundum** | Scratches topaz |\n| 10 | **Diamond** | Scratches everything! |\n\n**Rule:** A harder material can scratch a softer material.\n\n### Examples:\n\n**Very Hard:**\n- Diamond - Hardest natural material (used in cutting tools)\n- Sapphire - Used in scratch-resistant phone screens\n- Tungsten carbide - Used in drill bits\n\n**Hard:**\n- Steel - Used in knives, tools\n- Glass - Moderate hardness\n\n**Soft:**\n- Gold - Beautiful but scratches easily\n- Aluminum - Relatively soft metal\n- Plastic - Scratches with use\n- Wood - Can be dented\n\n### Singapore Applications:\n\n**Phone Screens:**\n- Gorilla Glass (contains alumino-silicate)\n- Hardness ~6-7 on Mohs scale\n- Resistant to scratches from keys, coins\n\n**Hawker Center Tables:**\n- Stainless steel tables resist scratches and dents\n- Easier to clean and maintain\n\n**Floor Tiles:**\n- Ceramic tiles are hard (resist scratching from shoes)\n- Porcelain is harder than ceramic\n\n---\n\n## Flexibility\n\n**Definition:** The ability of a material to bend without breaking.\n\n**Related Terms:**\n- **Flexible (Ductile)**: Can bend significantly without breaking\n- **Brittle**: Breaks easily without bending\n- **Elastic**: Returns to original shape after bending\n- **Plastic**: Stays bent after force is removed\n\n### Examples:\n\n**Highly Flexible:**\n- Rubber bands - Stretches and returns to shape\n- Plastic rulers - Bends and returns to shape\n- Copper wire - Can be bent into shapes\n- Fabric - Folds easily\n\n**Moderately Flexible:**\n- Paper - Bends but may crease permanently\n- Thin wood - Bends slightly\n- Aluminum foil - Bends and stays bent\n\n**Rigid/Brittle (Not Flexible):**\n- Glass - Shatters instead of bending\n- Ceramic - Breaks cleanly\n- Concrete - Cracks under bending\n- Cast iron - Snaps under stress\n\n### Singapore Applications:\n\n**Water Pipes (PVC):**\n- Flexible enough to curve around corners\n- Doesn't crack like brittle materials\n- Used throughout HDB buildings\n\n**Electrical Wires:**\n- Copper is flexible (can be bent during installation)\n- Surrounded by flexible plastic insulation\n- Easy to route through walls\n\n**Packaging:**\n- Plastic bags are flexible (can be folded, stuffed)\n- Glass bottles are rigid (more likely to break)\n- Flexible packaging reduces shipping damage\n\n---\n\n## Comparing Properties\n\n### Material Selection Examples:\n\n**1. Cutting Board:**\n- Need: Moderate hardness (won't dull knife quickly)\n- Use: Wood or plastic (not glass - too hard, damages knives)\n\n**2. HDB Window Grilles:**\n- Need: High strength, hard, rigid\n- Use: Steel bars (strong, won't bend easily)\n\n**3. Sports Shoe Soles:**\n- Need: Flexible, moderate strength\n- Use: Rubber (bends with foot movement, doesn't break)\n\n**4. Food Container:**\n- Need: Flexible (for opening/closing), moderate strength\n- Use: Plastic (glass would be too rigid and fragile)\n\n---\n\n## Trade-offs\n\nOften, improving one property weakens another:\n\n**Hardness vs. Flexibility:**\n- Very hard materials (diamond, glass) are often brittle\n- Flexible materials (rubber, plastic) are usually softer\n\n**Strength vs. Weight:**\n- Strong materials (steel) are often heavy\n- Lightweight materials (foam) are usually weak\n\n**Solution: Composite Materials**\n- Combine materials to get best of both\n- Example: Steel-reinforced concrete (strong + hard)\n- Example: Fiberglass (lightweight + strong)\n- Example: Carbon fiber (very strong + very light + expensive)',
      'content_zh': '# 强度、硬度和柔韧性（G3）\n\n注意：此部分对**G2学生是可选的**，但对G3学生是必需的。\n\n---\n\n## 强度\n\n**定义：** 材料承受施加力而不断裂的能力。\n\n### 强度类型：\n\n**1. 拉伸强度**（拉动）\n- 断裂前能承受多大的拉力\n- 重要用途：绳索、电缆、链条\n\n**2. 压缩强度**（推/挤）\n- 坍塌前能承受多大的挤压力\n- 重要用途：建筑支柱、地基\n\n**3. 剪切强度**（切割）\n- 通过滑动断裂前能承受多大的力\n- 重要用途：螺栓、铆钉\n\n### 例子：\n\n**高强度：**\n- 钢 - 用于组屋建筑框架\n- 混凝土 - 用于地基\n- 凯夫拉 - 用于防弹背心\n- 蜘蛛丝 - 比钢更强（按重量！）\n\n**低强度：**\n- 纸 - 容易撕裂\n- 泡沫 - 在重量下坍塌\n- 黏土 - 用很小的力就断裂\n\n### 新加坡应用：\n\n**地铁轨道：**\n- 必须有高压缩强度（重型列车）\n- 使用钢合金\n\n**吊桥：**\n- 电缆需要高拉伸强度\n- 由扭曲的钢丝制成\n\n**组屋墙壁：**\n- 混凝土有高压缩强度\n- 钢筋增加拉伸强度\n\n---\n\n## 硬度\n\n**定义：** 材料抵抗划痕、压痕或磨损的能力。\n\n### 莫氏硬度表（1-10）：\n\n| 等级 | 材料 | 可以划痕？ |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| 1 | **滑石** | 指甲可划 |\n| 2 | **石膏** | 指甲可划 |\n| 3 | **方解石** | 铜币可划 |\n| 4 | **萤石** | 刀可划 |\n| 5 | **磷灰石** | 刀难划 |\n| 6 | **长石** | 可划玻璃 |\n| 7 | **石英** | 容易划玻璃 |\n| 8 | **黄玉** | 可划石英 |\n| 9 | **刚玉** | 可划黄玉 |\n| 10 | **钻石** | 可划所有东西！ |\n\n**规则：** 更硬的材料可以划伤更软的材料。\n\n### 例子：\n\n**非常硬：**\n- 钻石 - 最硬的天然材料（用于切割工具）\n- 蓝宝石 - 用于防刮手机屏幕\n- 碳化钨 - 用于钻头\n\n**硬：**\n- 钢 - 用于刀具、工具\n- 玻璃 - 中等硬度\n\n**软：**\n- 金 - 美丽但容易划伤\n- 铝 - 相对较软的金属\n- 塑料 - 使用会划伤\n- 木头 - 可以凹陷\n\n### 新加坡应用：\n\n**手机屏幕：**\n- 大猩猩玻璃（含铝硅酸盐）\n- 莫氏硬度约6-7\n- 抗钥匙、硬币的划痕\n\n**小贩中心桌子：**\n- 不锈钢桌子抗划痕和凹陷\n- 更容易清洁和维护\n\n**地板瓷砖：**\n- 陶瓷砖坚硬（抗鞋子划痕）\n- 瓷器比陶瓷更硬\n\n---\n\n## 柔韧性\n\n**定义：** 材料弯曲而不断裂的能力。\n\n**相关术语：**\n- **柔韧（延性）**：可以显著弯曲而不断裂\n- **脆性**：容易断裂而不弯曲\n- **弹性**：弯曲后恢复原形\n- **塑性**：力移除后保持弯曲\n\n### 例子：\n\n**高度柔韧：**\n- 橡皮筋 - 拉伸并恢复形状\n- 塑料尺 - 弯曲并恢复形状\n- 铜线 - 可以弯曲成形状\n- 织物 - 容易折叠\n\n**中等柔韧：**\n- 纸 - 弯曲但可能永久折痕\n- 薄木头 - 轻微弯曲\n- 铝箔 - 弯曲并保持弯曲\n\n**刚性/脆性（不柔韧）：**\n- 玻璃 - 破碎而不是弯曲\n- 陶瓷 - 干净断裂\n- 混凝土 - 弯曲时开裂\n- 铸铁 - 在压力下断裂\n\n### 新加坡应用：\n\n**水管（PVC）：**\n- 足够柔韧以绕过角落\n- 不像脆性材料那样开裂\n- 在整个组屋建筑中使用\n\n**电线：**\n- 铜是柔韧的（安装时可以弯曲）\n- 被柔韧的塑料绝缘包围\n- 容易穿过墙壁布线\n\n**包装：**\n- 塑料袋是柔韧的（可以折叠、塞入）\n- 玻璃瓶是刚性的（更容易破碎）\n- 柔韧的包装减少运输损坏\n\n---\n\n## 比较性质\n\n### 材料选择示例：\n\n**1. 砧板：**\n- 需要：中等硬度（不会快速使刀钝）\n- 使用：木头或塑料（不是玻璃 - 太硬，损坏刀）\n\n**2. 组屋窗户护栏：**\n- 需要：高强度、硬、刚性\n- 使用：钢筋（坚固，不易弯曲）\n\n**3. 运动鞋底：**\n- 需要：柔韧、中等强度\n- 使用：橡胶（随脚部运动弯曲，不断裂）\n\n**4. 食品容器：**\n- 需要：柔韧（用于打开/关闭）、中等强度\n- 使用：塑料（玻璃太刚性和易碎）\n\n---\n\n## 权衡\n\n通常，改善一个性质会削弱另一个：\n\n**硬度与柔韧性：**\n- 非常硬的材料（钻石、玻璃）通常是脆性的\n- 柔韧的材料（橡胶、塑料）通常更软\n\n**强度与重量：**\n- 强材料（钢）通常很重\n- 轻质材料（泡沫）通常很弱\n\n**解决方案：复合材料**\n- 结合材料以获得两者的最佳性能\n- 例子：钢筋混凝土（强 + 硬）\n- 例子：玻璃纤维（轻 + 强）\n- 例子：碳纤维（非常强 + 非常轻 + 昂贵）'
